I love Scorsese films but this was a 6.5/10 for me, maybe a 7 at a push. The de-aging didn't work for me either, the faces were mostly OK but the necks looked weird and the bodies moved like old men. Pesci and De Niro were excellent as old men however, I think the movie would have worked a lot better had he cast younger actors for the younger roles and kept those guys for the old roles, there wouldn't have been any de-aging weirdness and you would have had fresh faces for most of the story to avoid 'gangster fatigue'

My first time here and as a boomer and life-long Scorcese fan I've got to say this reviewer is right on the money in his analysis of what could be the swan song of 20th-century American gangster movies. Chris Stuckmann has a discerning eye -- he is able to deconstruct the elements of a film that make it special and sensitize us to them without spoiling the experience of watching it for the first time. 


In this case the magic is in the legendary pairing of Scorcese and his New York criminal characters as played by Dr Niro, Pesci, Keitel, as well as a first for Scorcese,  Al Pacino. I agree with the reviewer: it works, magnificently. We are presented with a portrayal of once-violent men in their contemplative years, faced with the consequences of their past. I know it sounds boring but it's not because we come to care so much about the characters. 


The de-aging process, once we've acknowledged it's at work, does not call attention to itself -- we accept the characters' appearance at earlier stages of their lives more readily than makeup could do because this digital process is almost seamless. Expect to see a lot more of this process in the future.


If you have a Netflix account, there's a video interview available where the movie's principals discuss the project and their challenges. But I recommend that before you see it you watch the movie. Thanks to Netflix, this can be done on your home theater system. If you're like me, you don't miss the typical movie theater, with its filth, high prices, noisy audiences, and the distraction of multiple cell phone screens. I waited to watch this film on my big Sony at 4K, which produces a better picture than any cineplex projector can. Especially with a 3.5 hour film, it's nice to be able to pause the playback once in a while. Happy viewing and enjoy!

Easily the most engaging film I've seen in a very long time and brilliant in every way. I would like to focus, however, on Joe Pesci. I have never been so emotionally moved by a performance in at least the past 10 years. I think it's due to his volatile behavior that we have come to expect in his prior Scorsese films. Only this time, he has moved to the top and wields the ultimate power he was never able to achieve in Goodfellas and Casino. But, now he's older, wiser, restrained... and sad. For all of his power and success, all he could focus on was to be loved and it tore him apart when Peggy Sheeran wouldn't reciprocate that love and respect. This is a movie about sadness and regret. Where did it get them? Convictions, dying in jail and estrangement from what really matters:  family. I loved this film, but I was incredibly sad and devastated at the end. Like the end of an era that I never wanted to end. Hell, even the violence and the size of the guns were smaller and more restrained. All in the backdrop of a changing era, with the death of Kennedy squarely in the background. It was a film about death, sorrow, regret and change, which is inevitable. Scorsese seemed to be passing the torch to the next generation in hopes that something better might emerge. The final scene with DeNiro is gut-wrenching and I will carry that forever. I still feel it in the pit of my stomach and I've never been as upset by a film until now. A stunning achievement so well done, that I almost wish it wasn't.

This movie was one of the most painful movie viewing experiences of my life for the following reasons:  (1) a 3.5 hour film that sucked...so boring...dragged on for like ever....made my eyes bleed...arrrggghh...and keep in mind that you're talking to a guy who loves space odyssey 2001 and better call saul....so slow-moving and quiet is not a problem for me  (2) it was a martin scorscese film that sucked...you see, i think Casino is one of the best films ever made...pure magic...so to see one of my fav directors go down like this...it was painful...to those of you who say that scorcese was trying to artistically depart from films like casino, i respectfully disagree....first off, you can see that he was consciously or subconsciously trying to recreate the same magic of casino with hilarious vignettes and a great continuous soundtrack, but failed.... not once in this film was there one cool funny vignette that scorcese and his players are famous for...not a one......that wet fish car seat scene was a fail, and a scene best forgotten...how about when deniro stormed out of the meeting where pacino was yelling at the teamster execs and pacino was trying to get him to come back to the meeting...you could see that they were all trying to create that humorous lightness but yet again failed to connect....if you think about it, the irishman was a logical prequel (so to speak) of casino since it was the mob-infested teamsters union that provided the financing for the tangiers casino in casino.....the magic of scorcese, pacino and deniro is gone...face it guys, this was scorcese's Godfather 3....(3) robert deniro sucked...again, i love much of his previous work...his performance in casino was flawless...so to see him fall like this...painful...for over 3 hours he acted in a limited "phone it in" way with his mumbling frowny-mouthed charicaturish mannerisms...also, i wish he would stay out of politics...he just don't (sic) sound too bright....(4) al pacino totally sucked....quite honestly, it's painful to see him act in anything post scarface...in my opinion his role as tony montana was one of the greatest acting performances of all time..so to see this once-great actor continue his fall...super painful....first off, he trashed his voice from probably smoking, drinking, and snorting too much through the years...he talks like he's clearing his throat...hoo wah....but he also seems to have fried his brain cuz the guy can't act no more (sic)...his monologues seem to waiver between prior characters he has played instead of the character he asposed to play...a mix, if you will, between tony montana and that hoo wah guy from scent of a woman...there is no consistency of presence in his performances....there was zero chemistry between him and sheeran's daughter peggy...when he gave speeches to the teamsters, he just yelled with high energy, but again, zero chemistry...not once did i feel any connection with him......(5) totally miscast joe pesci....after casino, pesci established himself as the greatest psychopathic mobster on film of all time....so to cast him as a soft-spoken rational man...well, that's a miscast of the highest order.......although i will say that joe pesci did a fine job...after seeing this film, i have found my life's purpose:  and that is to dissuade others from seeing the irishman....it's a train wreck in slow motion.....just don't

And people saying Scorsese is right about Superhero movies need to get their head out of their ass ... yes most of them are mediocre at best ... but I watch the the Dark Knight, Thor Ragnarok and the First Guardians of the Galaxy over this hot mess any day... 


Also Scorsese probably said it because he doesn't really understand  the appeal of a superhero movie, he only understand mob culture of the 50's, 60's and 70's ..because that's where he grew up in and after 40 years of making movies in that genre doesn't know anything else anymore ... what's your excuse besides copying a renowned filmmaker's opinion to sound smart

While I was watching THE IRISHMAN, pinpointing the best scenes was quite easy. During the 1st part, it's when mob bosses RUSS BUFALINO and ANGELO BRUNO tell hitman FRANK SHEERAN (the title character) that he's in the middle of a betrayal plan without him knowing about it. During the 2nd part, it's when labor union leader JIMMY HOFFA and mob captain ANTHONY "TONY PRO" PROVENZANO start arguing about the latter not arriving to their meeting on time, which escalates until issues from the past are brought up. The thing is that these scenes are more personal. Even if the topic of discussion is something trivial (like whether or not traffic is a valid excuse for being late), it's compelling because of how much it means to the characters. Most of the movie unfortunately consists of talking from a business point of view. Of course that the characters are invested in what they're saying, but the stakes are different. It's not bad per se, but a more human approach would've helped the 210 minutes pass by a lot faster. During the 3rd part, the tone completely changes, and the number of great scenes increases. The pop songs and the over-realiance on narration are put aside (there's not even a lot of music score anymore either), which is more impactful. The de-aging effects are great, but it's hard to praise Rodrigo Prieto's cinematography. For the most part, the use of lighting and colors is pretty standard. Only 1/3 of the time he uses wide shots, crane shots and tracking shots. As I said before, the running time is mainly dedicated to conversations, and they're mostly filmed through close-ups and medium shots and edited with the shot-reverse-shot technique. I get that PEGGY SHEERAN (FRANK's daughter) only talking briefly in one scene (as an adult, at least) was done on purpose to make her words stick with the viewer more. I get that a good actress was still required in order to convey her thoughts without speaking. However, she doesn't get that many "dramatically silent" moments. She's practically an extra who happens to be in the center of the shot at times. I'm saying this because it was a good opportunity to cast an unknown actress and so she could have her big break. Using a famous and experienced actress like Anna Paquin felt like a waste. Was Al Pacino method-acting to the point where he was afraid he would disappear like his character did in real life? That would explain why he overacts like there's no tomorrow. Robert De Niro and Joe Pesci's performances are good. An advice to new directors out there: Using slow motion has to have a true purpose beyond being just a stylistic choice. It must highlight the intensity of the scene (dramatically or comedically) and help the audience pay attention to something that would be easy to miss otherwise. A bride and his father walking down the aisle with nothing else going on? Not needed. Especially if she's portrayed only as the daughter of a supporting character (I'm pretty sure we don't even find out what her name is).

Man, I still can't get over how weird they all look with the "de-aging" software... It's hard to put your finger on it.. Their skin looks good and all that, I also think they did a great job with the software, it's actually mind blowing, but it's like there are things that stick out soooooo much! Their noses are still huge old man noses, and their lips look weird when they talk, and the eyes look old... I don't know, it's like they can take the age out of the face, but they can't take the age out of their mannerisms, or their MOVEMENTS!!! Holy crap, it's so weird to see someone that is supposed to be like 30, moving like an 80 year old... The scene where Deniro kicks the crap out of the store owner, if you pay attention you'll see some serious errors, like when the door window breaks, and the way Deniro is moving is just so old man like.... It makes this seriously bad ass character go from being scary as hell to seeming like a geriatric and ruining that immersion.. It's very distracting. Just when you start forgetting about the de-aging software, something like that happens and pulls you right out of the world.. All that being said, it's still fun... A nostalgia ride... Not as good as the other classics you mentioned, but still... It's a new Scorsese gangster flick with an all star line up... Hard to complain, the second you start hearing the "Do whop" music, it brings you right back to that first time you watched Goodfellas, and you can't help but get a little excited... I just wish they would have made it 10-15 years ago and youthed people up with makeup and lighting...

My favorite Scorsese movies are RAGING BULL and THE WOLF OF WALL STREET. I'm afraid that THE IRISHMAN doesn't even come close. While I was watching it, pinpointing the best scenes was quite easy. During the 1st part, it's when mob bosses RUSS BUFALINO and ANGELO BRUNO tell hitman FRANK SHEERAN (the title character) that he's in the middle of a betrayal plan without him knowing about it. During the 2nd part, it's when labor union leader JIMMY HOFFA and mob captain ANTHONY "TONY PRO" PROVENZANO start arguing about the latter not arriving to their meeting on time, which escalates until issues from the past are brought up. The thing is that these scenes are more personal. Even if the topic of discussion is something trivial (like whether or not traffic is a valid excuse for being late), it's compelling because of how much it means to the characters. Most of the movie unfortunately consists of talking from a business point of view. Of course that the characters are invested in what they're saying, but the stakes are different. It's not bad per se, but a more human approach would've helped the 210 minutes pass by a lot faster. During the 3rd part, the tone completely changes, and the number of great scenes increases. The pop songs and the over-realiance on narration are put aside (there's not even a lot of music score anymore either), which is more impactful. The de-aging effects are great, but it's hard to praise Rodrigo Prieto's cinematography. For the most part, the use of lighting and colors is pretty standard. Only 1/3 of the time he uses wide shots, crane shots and tracking shots. As I said before, the running time is mainly dedicated to conversations, and they're mostly filmed through close-ups and medium shots and edited with the shot-reverse-shot technique. I get that PEGGY SHEERAN (FRANK's daughter) only talking briefly in one scene (as an adult, at least) was done on purpose to make her words stick with the viewer more. I get that a good actress was still required in order to convey her thoughts without speaking. However, she doesn't get that many "dramatically silent" moments. She's practically an extra who happens to be in the center of the shot at times. I'm saying this because it was a good opportunity to cast an unknown actress and so she could have her big break. Using a famous and experienced actress like Anna Paquin felt like a waste. Was Al Pacino method-acting to the point where he was afraid he would disappear like his character did in real life? That would explain why he overacts like there's no tomorrow. Robert De Niro and Joe Pesci's performances are good. An advice to new directors out there: Using slow motion has to have a true purpose beyond being just a stylistic choice. It must highlight the intensity of the scene (dramatically or comedically) and help the audience pay attention to something that would be easy to miss otherwise. A bride and his father walking down the aisle with nothing else going on? Not needed. Especially if she's portrayed only as the daughter of a supporting character (I'm pretty sure we don't even find out what her name is).

Unpopular opinion here, The Irishman was not that good. Look guys, Martin Scorsese is one of the reasons I started watching quality cinema. Goodfellas, Taxi Driver, Casino, The Departed and the like are phenomenal films that will undoubtedly stand the test of time. Make no mistake as to how excited I was to see The Irishman and how much I love Scorsese's work. But instead of the mob epic that the critics have been raving about all I saw was a long-winded, meandering mess in dire need of editing. Plot points were very repetitive and scenes that added absolutely nothing lingered on for way too long and for no good reason. The de-aging technology was distracting as it was poorly done. DeNiro looked like he had a slightly younger face for past scenes but still moved like an old man. Moreover, the film's message didn't need such an obscene runtime to be brought across. If The Irishman didn't have Scorsese's name in addition to this fine roster of actors attached, it would've been shat all over. Tell me with a straight face that this film holds a candle to Goodfellas. I think people are talking about The Irishman because Scorsese made disparaging remarks bout Marvel films before it was released, thereby creating a mass dichotomy of "real cinephiles" vs "mindless Marvel fanboys", thereby alienating those who had legitimate criticism about The Irishman and putting them in the latter category. Marty bit off more than he can chew this time, and there's no shame in admitting it.

This movie was one of the most painful movie viewing experiences of my life for the following reasons:  (1) a 3.5 hour film that sucked...so boring...dragged on for like ever....made my eyes bleed...arrrggghh  (2) it was a martin scorscese film that sucked...i think Casino is one of the best films ever made...pure magic...so to see one of my fav directors go down like this...it was painful...to those of you who say that scorcese was trying to artistically depart from films like casino, i respectfully disagree....first off, you can see that he was consciously or subconsciously trying to recreate the same magic of casino with hilarious vignettes and a great continuous soundtrack, but failed.... not once in this film was there one cool funny vignette that scorcese and his players are famous for...not a one......that wet fish car seat scene was a fail, and a scene best forgotten...how about when deniro stormed out of the meeting where pacino was yelling at the teamster execs and pacino was trying to get him to come back to the meeting...you could see that they were all trying to create that humorous lightness but yet again failed to connect....if you think about it, the irishman was the logical prequel to casino since it was the mob-infested teamsters union that provided the financing for the tangiers casino in casino.....the magic of scorcese, pacino and deniro is gone...face it guys, this was scorcese's Godfather 3....(3) robert deniro sucked...again, i love much of his previous work...his performance in casino was flawless...so to see him fall like this...painful...for over 3 hours he acted in a limited "phone it in" way with his mumbling frowny-mouthed caricaturish mannerisms...also, i wish he would stay out of politics...he just don't (sic) sound too bright....(4) al pacino totally sucked....quite honestly, it's painful to see him act in anything post scarface...in my opinion his role as tony montana was one of the greatest acting performances of all time..so to see this once-great actor continue his fall...super painful....first off, he trashed his voice from probably smoking, drinking, and snorting too much through the years...he talks like he's clearing his throat...hoo wah....but he also seems to have fried his brain cuz the guy can't act no more (sic)...his monologues seem to waiver between prior characters he has played instead of the character he was asposed (sic) to play...a mix, if you will, between tony montana and that hoo wah guy from skent (sic) of a woman...there is no consistency of presence in his performances....there was zero chemistry between him and sheeran's daughter peggy...when he gave speeches to the teamsters onion (sic), he just yelled with high energy...but again, zero chemistry...not once did i feel any connection with him......(5) totally miscast joe pesci....after casino, pesci established himself as the greatest psychopathic mobster on film of all time....so to cast him as a soft-spoken rational man...well, that's a miscast of the highest order.......although i will say that joe pesci did a fine job...after seeing this film, i have found my life's purpose:  and that is to dissuade others from seeing the irishman....it's a train wreck in slow motion.....just don't

OK, I was so hyped for this film, had the book over 10 years, heard Scorcese was making it about 8 years ago.  This is the Best story of any of his movies.  So yeah, was somewhat happy with the outcome:
The Title:  HA HA, it Isn't 'The Irishman'.  The REAL Title is the same as the book:  'I Hear You Paint Houses', kudos Martin  :)
Pesci kills it as Russel Buffalino, he deserves another best supporting statue.  The movie chugs along fine early on.  It's when it gets to the Hoffa stuff like 1 1/2 - 2 hours in that it starts to falter and the Missed Opportunities of not showing things in the book begin to pile up.
Scenes that would have been necessary to really establish the close bond between Frank and Jimmy that weren't shown:

Not showing more of the conflict in Detroit with the rival cab company, Frank marching up to their headquarters single handedly to face their leader, Crucial scene to show the kind of balls he really had.
The scene where Jimmy marches into a meeting filled with members of the rival company backed up only by Frank.  The omission of this material really hindered any sense of how much Jimmy really depended on Frank. 

Then the 'Get Hoffa' part, I only knew what was really going on because I read the book.
Nothing about the first trial, Jimmy playing the 'race card' beautifully.  Joe Louis & the black lady attorney from SF he hired meet and got married.
It was essential for the movie to go into this stuff more to establish the fact that it was Jimmy Hoffa who put Jimmy Hoffa away.  HE bribed when he had his cases won but he was his own worst enemy.  This is important because this was a Legitimate reason as to why the mob wanted him whacked.  Sometimes he made bad decisions and became his own worst enemy.  But the movie fails with this. 

Pacino as Jimmy Hoffa, inconsistent, better in certain scenes than in others.  The lady who plays Jo Hoffa who played the babysitter in Goodfellas is great though.
Other Painful omissions that Should Have been included:
The second scene with David Ferrie, the JFK assassination stuff ("Heya Frank, long time no see..")
The payoff scene with Attorney General John Mitchell ("These things don't come cheap", and 'whoosh' went the briefcase..)

Â At the end, I was expecting reflections on what little legacy he left:
The Italian mob is gone, unions are nothing to speak of anymore including the Teamsters, all that's left is Vegas, not anything to feel proud of after all the bullshit and killing.
But it wasn't there, Frank doesn't reconcile with his daughters and then picks out a coffin for himself.
The end,  too bad, could've been So Much More Meaningful..

I Love Scorsese's films, but this was one, is just one too many. It lacked tight editing, scenes lingered far too long to make artistic points. The technology of that allowed the actors to be made younger was not impressive given the actors could not move as if they were younger. The one scene that made this point, was when De Niro's character roughs up a corner grocer for shoving his daughter. The scene is difficult to watch given De Niro seemed to struggle as much with his own lack of mobility to carry off the fight scene realistically despite having the willing and compliant younger actor. Al Pacino's character looked nothing like Hoffa. Yes the acting was good in general, but the story was just too drawn out and slow and the characters were just not that interesting to hold your attention. As a man of 58, the hardest fact is recognizing the increasing limitation as we age, this movie opens with De Niro's character in an assisted care facility. It is where this movie should have stayed. The Actors and Directors are all legends, but this movie only took away from some of their carrier luster.

1) Include far more of the RFK/Hoffa conflict that, in real-life, dominated television back in the day. It was a celebrity feud in a way that today it could never be. Also, they left out the IMPORTANT aspect of Nixon pardoning Hoffa with the proviso of not running for president of the Union, until 1980. Which pissed the real-life Hoffa off. Why leave that out, I don't get it!

Scorsese, along with his amazing cast(s), always nails the culture and atmosphere of the environment. You can tell they were transported back in time for the 3.5 hour running length. The mark of a great storyteller (visually, in this case).
